DATA = {
    "1": {
        "2": "<p><strong>vayyedabber shelomoh lechol-yisraʾel lesarei ha'alafim</strong> — 'Solomon spoke to all Israel, to the commanders of thousands.' The verb <em>dibber</em> (H1696) with <em>lechol-yisraʾel</em> signals a covenantal assembly (cf. Deut 1:1). The military terminology — <em>sarei ha'alafim</em> (commanders of thousands), <em>sarei hame'ot</em> (hundreds), <em>shofetim</em> (judges), <em>nesiʾim</em> (leaders) — mirrors Moses's organizational structure in Deut 1:15, implicitly casting Solomon as the new Moses leading Israel in its covenant life.</p>",
        "3": "<p><strong>vayyelechu shelomoh ve'kol-haqqahal immo</strong> — 'Solomon and all the assembly with him went.' The destination is Gibeon (<em>haqqahal</em> = the assembly), where the Tent of Meeting was located since the Gibeonites had preserved it from Shiloh (cf. Josh 9). Gibeon's elevation as the primary high place had Mosaic legitimacy: the Tent of Meeting (<em>ʾōhel môʿēd</em>) and the bronze altar of Bezalel son of Uri resided there (v5). The Chronicler emphasizes this Mosaic pedigree to legitimize Solomon's worship.</p>",
        "4": "<p><strong>ʾăḇal ʾărôn hāʾĕlōhîm heʿĕlāh dāwîd</strong> — 'But the ark of God David had brought up.' This parenthetical note distinguishes two sacred sites: the ark was now in Jerusalem (in the tent David pitched — 2 Sam 6:17), while the Tabernacle furnishings were at Gibeon. The <em>ʾăḇal</em> ('but/however') marks a deliberate contrast, reassuring readers that the Chronicler's Solomon-story is Ark-centered; the Gibeon worship is secondary preparation, not the center of Israel's covenant life.</p>",
        "5": "<p><strong>umizbach hannechoshet ʾăšer ʿāśāh betsal'ʾēl ben-ûrî</strong> — 'the bronze altar that Bezalel son of Uri had made.' The Chronicler alone preserves this detail, tracing the altar's Mosaic provenance. <em>Betsal'ʾēl</em> (B'tsal'el, H1212 — 'in the shadow/protection of God') was the Spirit-filled craftsman of Exodus 31. The bronze altar (<em>mizbach hannechoshet</em>) was the legitimate place of sacrifice under the Mosaic covenant; situating Solomon at this altar connects his reign to the Sinai covenant structure rather than ad hoc Canaanite high-place worship.</p>",
        "6": "<p><strong>vayyaʿal shelomoh shammah ʿal mizbach hannechoshet</strong> — 'Solomon offered there on the bronze altar.' The verb <em>ʿālāh</em> (H5927 — to go up, to offer a burnt offering) gives the idiom <em>ʿōlāh</em> (burnt offering, ascending sacrifice). The <em>ʾelef ʿōlōt</em> (thousand burnt offerings) is a royal gesture of extraordinary commitment, analogous to David's offerings at the ark's installation (1 Chr 16:2). The extraordinary quantity signals the seriousness of Solomon's approach to God — this is not casual worship but deliberate seeking.</p>",
        "8": "<p><strong>vayyōmer ʾělōhîm lišelōmōh maʾ ʾettenāh-lāk</strong> — 'God said to Solomon, Ask what I shall give you.' The formula is the theophanic grant-of-request pattern found at Sinai (Exod 33:17-19) and in the patriarchal stories (Gen 15:2). In the Solomonic narrative (cf. 1 Kgs 3:5) this occurs in a dream at night. The Chronicler's version omits the 'dream' detail, likely to universalize the theophany — it is a direct divine encounter, not merely a dream-oracle, emphasizing Solomon's unique standing as the chosen temple-builder.</p>",
        "9": "<p><strong>ʿattāh YHWH ʾĕlōhîm yaʾaman devarkha ʿim-dāwîd ʾāḇî</strong> — 'Now, LORD God, let your word to David my father be confirmed.' <em>Yaʾaman</em> (from H539 ʾāman — to be firm, reliable, trustworthy) is the root of <em>ʾemûnāh</em> (faithfulness) and <em>ʾāmēn</em>. Solomon's prayer grounds his petition in the Davidic covenant promise (2 Sam 7; 1 Chr 17), invoking God's own commitment to keep His word. <em>ʿim-dāwîd ʾāḇî</em> establishes covenantal continuity — the new king stands on the covenant foundation laid by his father.</p>",
        "10": "<p><strong>ʿattāh ḥoḵmāh ûmaddāʿ ten-lî</strong> — 'Now give me wisdom and knowledge.' <em>Ḥoḵmāh</em> (H2451 — skill, wisdom, practical competence for leadership) pairs with <em>madda</em> (H4093 — knowledge, understanding, science — a word rare in the Bible, appearing also in Dan 1:4,17). Together they form the ideal of royal discernment. Solomon asks not for power, wealth, or victory but for the capacity to govern justly — fulfilling the Deuteronomic ideal of a king who writes the Torah and lives by it (Deut 17:18-20), leading a people God identifies as too vast to number (<em>ʿam rav</em>).</p>",
        "11": "<p><strong>yaʿan ʾăšer hāytāh zōʾt ʿim-levāvekā</strong> — 'Because this was in your heart.' <em>Levāv</em> (H3824 — heart, the seat of will and intention) is the Chronicler's key term for authentic worship (cf. 1 Chr 28:9). God's response reveals that the request itself is evidence of Solomon's character — the kind of king who asks for wisdom rather than wealth signals a heart already oriented toward God's purposes. This is the Chronicler's theology of <em>darāš</em> (seeking God): when one seeks rightly, God responds generously.</p>",
        "13": "<p><strong>vayyāšāḇ shelomoh min-habāmāh ʾăšer-begibʿôn</strong> — 'Solomon returned from the high place at Gibeon.' The verb <em>šūb</em> (H7725 — to return, turn back) marks the transition from sacred encounter to historical action. The Chronicler's narrative pacing is deliberate: the Gibeon theophany is the spiritual foundation for everything that follows — the temple-building, the administrative system, the empire. Solomon does not act on his own initiative; he acts as the anointed king who has received divine authorization and endowment. The return to Jerusalem signals the shift from receiving to executing.</p>",
        "14": "<p><strong>vayyeʾsof shelomoh markāḇôt ûfārāšîm</strong> — 'Solomon gathered chariots and cavalry.' The Chronicler lists Solomon's military-commercial capacity (<em>ʾelef ʾarbaʿ-meʾōt markāḇôt</em> = 1,400 chariots; <em>šnêm-ʿāśār ʾelef pārāšîm</em> = 12,000 cavalry), situating them in garrison cities. The Deuteronomic law (Deut 17:16) warned kings not to multiply horses, particularly through Egypt (<em>mitsrayim</em>). The Chronicler includes this data neutrally (unlike the Deuteronomistic Historian's implied critique) — the focus is on Solomon's administrative power as context for the temple project, not as moral evaluation.</p>",
        "15": "<p><strong>vayyitten hammelekh ʾet-hakkesep veʾet-hazzāhāḇ</strong> — 'The king made silver and gold as plentiful as stones.' <em>Kessep</em> (H3701 — silver, money) and <em>zāhāḇ</em> (H2091 — gold) becoming as common as <em>ʾăḇānîm</em> (stones) is hyperbole of royal bounty. The comparison to the Shefelah's cedar forests (<em>šiqmîm baššĕfēlāh</em>) grounds the abstraction in a Palestinian landscape. The Chronicler is showing that God's promise — 'riches and honor' which Solomon did NOT ask for — was indeed granted, fulfilling v12.</p>",
        "16": "<p><strong>ûmôṣāʾ hassûsîm ʾăšer-lišelōmōh mimmitsrāyim</strong> — 'The horses Solomon imported came from Egypt.' The horse trade from <em>Mitsrayim</em> (Egypt) and <em>Qōweh</em> (Cilicia in SE Anatolia, identified with the Que of Assyrian texts) reflects Solomon's position at the nexus of the ancient Near Eastern trade networks. The price data — 150 silver shekels per horse, 600 per chariot (<em>markāḇāh</em>) — gives realistic commercial detail absent from many royal records but preserved here, likely from administrative archives to which the Chronicler had access.</p>",
        "17": "<p><strong>wayyōtsîʾû vayyōtsîʾû misrayim markāḇāh bešeš meʾōt kesep</strong> — 'They imported from Egypt a chariot for 600 silver shekels.' The verb <em>yātsāʾ</em> (H3318 — to go out, export) with the doubled form (<em>vayyōtsîʾû vayyōtsîʾû</em> in some traditions) may suggest regularized commercial export. The Chronicler's business precision — specific prices for chariots and horses, named routes via <em>yad hammelekhim</em> ('through the king's agents') — shows that Solomon's wisdom included economic administration. The phrase <em>vekhēn lehol-malkhê hachittîm velmalkhê ʾărām</em> places Solomon's commerce in a regional diplomatic matrix.</p>",
    },
    "2": {
        "1": "<p><strong>vayyōʾmer shelomoh livnôt bayit lešēm YHWH</strong> — 'Solomon determined to build a house for the name of the LORD.' <em>Bayit lešēm YHWH</em> (house for the Name of YHWH) is the Deuteronomic formula (Deut 12:5,11 — 'the place where YHWH will cause his name to dwell'). The Chronicler's theology of the divine Name (<em>hašēm</em>) avoids naive anthropomorphism: the temple is not God's house in the sense of physical residence but the place where His covenantal name is invoked and present. The <em>ûḇayit lemalkûto</em> (and a palace for his kingdom) pairs temple-building with state-building — sacred and civic architecture are intertwined projects.</p>",
        "2": "<p><strong>vayyispor shelomoh šibʿîm ʾelef sāḇāl</strong> — 'Solomon conscripted 70,000 burden-bearers.' The massive labor force — <em>šibʿîm ʾelef sāḇāl</em> (70,000 load-carriers), <em>šemônîm ʾelef ḥōṣeḇ</em> (80,000 stonecutters in the mountains), <em>šelōšet ʾălāfîm ûšešmeʾōt</em> (3,600 overseers) — is the Chronicler's version of 1 Kgs 5:13-16, where the corvée is slightly differently numbered. The scale reflects the temple's importance as a national project under royal organization. The Chronicler's higher number for overseers (3,600 vs 3,300) may reflect different counting conventions or the inclusion of additional supervisory ranks.</p>",
        "3": "<p><strong>vayyišlaḥ shelomoh ʾel-ḥûrām melek-tsôr</strong> — 'Solomon sent to Huram king of Tyre.' The Chronicler uses <em>Ḥûrām</em> where Kings uses <em>Ḥîrām</em>. Tyre (<em>Tsôr</em>) was the dominant Phoenician commercial city-state, renowned for its cedar forests and skilled craftsmen. Solomon's diplomatic letter (<em>kāʾăšer ʿāśîtā ʿim-dāwîd ʾāḇî</em> — 'as you did with David my father') appeals to the existing treaty relationship. The Chronicler's version expands the theological explanation of the temple's purpose — a passage not in Kings — making it explicitly a theological treatise on divine transcendence.</p>",
        "4": "<p><strong>hinnēh ʾănî ḇōneh-bayit lešēm YHWH ʾĕlōhāy</strong> — 'I am building a house for the name of the LORD my God.' Solomon's explanation to Hiram is one of the Bible's most sophisticated statements of temple theology. The temple is not a residence for God (<em>kî mî yaʾatsōr kōaḥ livnôt-lô bayit</em> — 'for who has the power to build him a house?') but a place for sacred service: <em>lehaqṭîr lefānāyw</em> (to burn incense before him), <em>maʾărekhet leḥem</em> (the bread of the Presence), <em>ʿōlōt laḇōqer velaʿereḇ</em> (burnt offerings morning and evening). The liturgical calendar (<em>šabbātôt, ḥăḏāšîm, môʿăḏê YHWH</em>) grounds the temple in Israel's covenantal time-keeping.</p>",
        "7": "<p><strong>veʿattāh šelaḥ-lî ʾîš ḥākām laʿăśôt</strong> — 'Now send me a skilled man to work.' Solomon requests a craftsman skilled in gold, silver, bronze, iron (<em>zahāḇ ûḵhesep ûneḥōšet ûḇarzel</em>), purple, crimson, and blue (<em>argāmān karmîl ûtəḵēlet</em>) — the full range of sacred textiles and metals from the Mosaic Tabernacle tradition (Exod 25-31). The craftsman request echoes Bezalel's endowment with the Spirit of God (Exod 31:3) — the Spirit-filled artisan is the human instrument through which the divine pattern becomes physical reality.</p>",
        "8": "<p><strong>ûšlaḥ-lî ʿătsê ʾărāzîm bərōšîm veʾalgûmmîm</strong> — 'Send me cedar, cypress, and algum timber from Lebanon.' The three timber species: <em>ʾărāzîm</em> (cedars — H730, the noble cedar of Lebanon, symbol of royal grandeur), <em>berōšîm</em> (cypresses — H1265, tall straight trees for beams and planking), <em>ʾalgûmmîm</em> (possibly red sandalwood or juniper — H418, used for musical instruments and stairs in 1 Kgs 10:12). Lebanon's forests (<em>haleḇānôn</em>) were the premium timber source of the ancient Near East — referenced in Assyrian, Egyptian, and Ugaritic texts as luxury exports essential for monumental construction.</p>",
        "9": "<p><strong>veʾanî ʾetnāh lechōṣeḇêkā ḥōṣĕḇê hāʿētsîm</strong> — 'I will provide for your servants who cut the timber.' Solomon's counteroffer specifies quantities of food for Hiram's workforce: <em>ʿeśrîm ʾelef kor ḥittîm</em> (20,000 cors of wheat), <em>ʿeśrîm ʾelef kor śeʿōrîm</em> (20,000 cors of barley), <em>ʿeśrîm ʾelef bat yayin</em> (20,000 baths of wine), <em>ʿeśrîm ʾelef bat šemen</em> (20,000 baths of oil). A <em>kor</em> (Homer) is approximately 220-230 liters; this represents the produce of a substantial portion of Israelite agricultural land, demonstrating the economic integration of Israel's surplus with Phoenician maritime timber resources.</p>",
        "10": "<p><strong>vayyōʾmer ḥûrām melek-tsôr bekhitāḇ</strong> — 'Huram king of Tyre replied in writing.' The exchange of written diplomatic letters (<em>kitāḇ</em> — document, letter) reflects the standard ANE protocol of inter-royal correspondence. Huram's letter opens with theological affirmation: <em>beʾahaḇat YHWH ʾet-ʿammô</em> (because of YHWH's love for his people). A pagan king acknowledging YHWH's love for Israel is remarkable — the Chronicler uses this to show that even Gentile rulers recognized the theological significance of the temple project. The letter form itself authenticated the diplomatic agreement.</p>",
        "11": "<p><strong>behaḥaḇat YHWH ʾet-ʿammô netankha ʿălêhem meleḵ</strong> — 'Because of YHWH's love for his people, he has made you king over them.' Huram's theological confession is the Chronicler's theological thesis: Solomon's kingship is not a political accident but YHWH's covenantal appointment. <em>ʾAhaḇāh</em> (H160 — love, covenant loyalty, election) is the Deuteronomic word for God's elective love (Deut 7:8 — 'because YHWH loves you'). Huram's recognition echoes the universal scope of YHWH's reputation: the nations see what Israel experiences through the covenant.</p>",
        "12": "<p><strong>ûvekhol-mĕlaʾkhāh yēḏaʿ ḥurām ʾāḇî</strong> — 'Huram my father is skilled in every craft.' The phrase <em>ḥurām ʾāḇî</em> (Huram my father/master) is the craftsman's honorific — <em>ʾāḇ</em> here means 'master craftsman' or 'chief artisan,' not biological father. This Huram is the son of a Danite woman and a Tyrian father (v14) — a bicultural artisan. The Chronicler describes his skill in terms that deliberately echo Bezalel's endowment (Exod 31:3): competence in gold, silver, bronze, iron (<em>zahāḇ, kesep, neḥōšet, barzel</em>), stone, and wood. The Spirit-filled artisan motif recurs: the temple's physical beauty is divinely provided.</p>",
        "13": "<p><strong>ûneḥōšet barzel ʾaḇen ûʿēts</strong> — 'bronze, iron, stone, and wood.' The comprehensive listing of Huram-abi's materials expertise continues: <em>argāmān, tĕkhēlet, ûḇûts, vekharmîl</em> (purple, violet/blue, fine linen, and crimson) are the four sacred textile colors of the Tabernacle (Exod 26:1,31,36). The mention of <em>pittûaḥ kol-pittûaḥ</em> (all manner of engraving) recalls Bezalel's specific skill in engraving (Exod 31:5). The Chronicler is constructing a careful typological parallel: as Bezalel built the Tabernacle under Moses, Huram-abi will build the Temple under Solomon — continuity of the sacred-art tradition.</p>",
        "15": "<p><strong>vehaḥittîm vehaśśeʿōrîm haššemen vehayyayin ʾăšer ʾāmar</strong> — 'the wheat, barley, oil, and wine which my lord has promised.' Hiram's response confirms the commercial treaty terms. The food provisions were critical infrastructure for the Phoenician workforce: the entire temple project depended on Israelite agricultural surplus sustaining Lebanese timber workers. This economic interdependence is a feature of the broader Pax Solomonica — Solomon's empire was held together not only by military power but by integrated economic arrangements that made cooperation mutually beneficial.</p>",
        "16": "<p><strong>vaʾănî nikrōt ʿētsîm min-haleḇānôn</strong> — 'I will cut timber from Lebanon.' The logistics: Phoenician craftsmen cut the timber on Lebanon's slopes, then made it into <em>rāpesôdôt</em> (log rafts) floated south along the Mediterranean coast to Joppa (<em>Yāfô</em>). From Joppa the timber would be transported overland up to Jerusalem — a significant engineering challenge given Jerusalem's elevation. This is the same route used by Ezra's returnees for the Second Temple (Ezra 3:7). The Chronicler's geographic precision grounds the narrative in the real logistics of monumental construction.</p>",
        "17": "<p><strong>vayyispor shelomoh kol-hāʾanāšîm haggērîm</strong> — 'Solomon counted all the resident aliens in Israel.' The <em>gērîm</em> (resident aliens, H1616 — sojourners, non-Israelites living in Israel's land) were a significant demographic. Solomon counted <em>šelōšāh veʾarbaʿîm ʾelef ûšloš meʾōt</em> (153,600 resident aliens), echoing Moses's census of the wilderness generation. The Chronicler's version specifies that these <em>gērîm</em> provided the labor force for the temple — the Tabernacle had been built by Israelites, but the Temple was built with a cosmopolitan workforce, anticipating its character as a house of prayer for all peoples (cf. 2 Chr 6:32-33).</p>",
        "18": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas mehhem šibʿîm ʾelef sāḇāl</strong> — 'He made 70,000 of them load-bearers.' The distribution of labor: <em>šibʿîm ʾelef sāḇāl</em> (70,000 burden-bearers), <em>šemônîm ʾelef ḥōṣēḇ bāhār</em> (80,000 stonecutters in the mountains), <em>šelōšet ʾălāfîm ûšešmeʾōt menatshîm laʿăśôt haʿām</em> (3,600 overseers to compel the workers). The organization mirrors the Mosaic camp structure. The total — 153,600 workers — represents the largest peacetime construction project in Israel's history. The workforce diversity (Israelites, resident aliens, Phoenicians) anticipates the temple's eventual purpose as a meeting place between YHWH and all nations.</p>",
    },
    "3": {
        "2": "<p><strong>vayyāḥel livnôt baḥōdeš haššēnî baššēnî yôm šeḇîʿî ûšelōšîm lišenāt ʾarbaʿ</strong> — 'He began to build in the second month, on the second day, in the fourth year of his reign.' The date formula is precise: the second month is <em>Iyyar</em> (April-May), 480 years after the Exodus according to 1 Kgs 6:1 (a number symbolizing 12 generations of 40 years). The Chronicler's date establishes that the temple-building happens within sacred time — not as a secular construction project but as the fulfillment of a divine timetable inaugurated at Sinai. Construction begins when spring weather permits quarrying and building in Jerusalem's limestone hills.</p>",
        "3": "<p><strong>veʾēlleh yusad shelomoh livnôt ʾet-bêt hāʾĕlōhîm</strong> — 'These are the foundations Solomon laid for building the house of God.' The Chronicler specifies the ground plan: <em>ha'ōreḵ ʾamôt beammāh harîšônāh šiššîm</em> (length 60 cubits by the old standard) and <em>harrōḥaḇ ʿeśrîm</em> (width 20 cubits). The 'old cubit' (<em>ammāh harîšônāh</em>) may be the longer royal cubit of approximately 52.5 cm (vs the standard cubit of 44.5 cm), making the Temple approximately 31.5m long by 10.5m wide. These measurements match the Tabernacle's proportions doubled, reinforcing the theological continuity between Mosaic and Solomonic worship.</p>",
        "4": "<p><strong>veʾûlām ʾăšer ʿal-penê hāʾōreḵ ʾal-penê rōḥaḇ-bêt</strong> — 'The vestibule in front of the nave of the house.' The <em>ʾûlām</em> (portico/vestibule — H197) measured 20 cubits wide (matching the temple's width) and 20 cubits high according to the MT of Chronicles (though 1 Kgs 6:3 gives 10 cubits for the depth). The phrase <em>vayyetsappu ʾotô min-happenîm zāhāḇ ṭāhôr</em> (he plated it within with pure gold) introduces the gold-plating motif that recurs throughout chs 3-4. The word <em>ṭāhôr</em> (pure, H2889) applied to gold signals ritual purity — the temple's materials must be commensurate with the presence of the holy God.</p>",
        "5": "<p><strong>veʾet habbayit haggādôl ṣippāh ʿēts bĕrôš</strong> — 'The great nave he paneled with cypress wood.' The interior paneling sequence: cypress (<em>bĕrôš</em>) boards overlaid with fine gold (<em>zāhāḇ ṭôḇ</em>), then decorated with <em>tīmôrôt</em> (palm tree designs — H8561) and <em>śarṣĕrôt</em> (chains). The <em>tīmôrôt</em> are the stylized palm-tree motifs familiar from Phoenician ivories and carved reliefs found at sites like Megiddo — a shared Syro-Palestinian iconographic vocabulary for royal sanctuary decoration. The chains (<em>śarṣĕrôt</em>) may be decorative swag-chain motifs or actual metal chain features between the palm carvings.</p>",
        "6": "<p><strong>vaytseṣap ʾet-habbayit ʾeben yeqārāh letipʾāret</strong> — 'He decorated the house with precious stones for beauty.' <em>Yeqārāh</em> (H3368 — precious, rare, costly) applied to stones signals the temple's status as the most valuable construction in Israel. The gold is specified as <em>zahāḇ Parvayim</em> (gold of Parvaim — H6516), an otherwise unknown toponym, perhaps in Arabia or East Africa, associated with the finest quality gold. The layering of beauty (<em>tipʾāret</em> — H8597, splendor, glory, honor) is deliberate theology: the temple's visual magnificence is a reflection of YHWH's own glory (<em>kāḇôd</em>) — earthly beauty pointing toward divine transcendence.</p>",
        "7": "<p><strong>vaytseṣap ʾet-habbayit haqqqîrôt vehasippîm</strong> — 'He overlaid the house — beams, thresholds, walls, and doors — with gold.' The total gold-plating of the sanctuary's structural elements (<em>qîrôt</em> = walls, <em>sippîm</em> = thresholds/doorposts, <em>dĕlātōtāyw</em> = doors) made the interior a golden room. The gold overlaying technique was well-attested in Egyptian and Mesopotamian temple construction; the closest biblical parallel is the Tabernacle's gold-plated ark and mercy seat (Exod 25:11,17). The <em>kĕrûḇîm</em> (cherubim) carved into the walls extend the Tabernacle's cherubim-decorated curtains (Exod 26:31) into three-dimensional architectural ornament.</p>",
        "9": "<p><strong>ûmišqal hammismĕrôt zahāḇ ḥămiššîm šĕqālîm</strong> — 'The weight of the nails was 50 gold shekels.' The detail about gold nails (<em>mismĕrôt zahāḇ</em> — H4548, fastening nails) weighing 50 shekels each (approximately 570 grams per nail) is remarkable — bronze or iron nails would normally suffice. The use of gold nails in structural joinery signals that not even the hidden fasteners of the building were allowed to be base metal. The <em>ʿăliôt</em> (upper chambers, H5944) were also overlaid with gold — total gold-plating, inside and out, floor to ceiling, even structurally.</p>",
        "10": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas beḇêt qōdĕš haqqŏdāšîm kerûḇîm šĕnayim</strong> — 'In the most holy place he made two cherubim of sculptured work.' The <em>qōdĕš haqqĕdāšîm</em> (holy of holies, most holy place) housed two giant cherubim (<em>kĕrûḇîm</em>), each standing 10 cubits tall (approx. 5m), with wingspan matching their height — so their combined outstretched wings spanned the full 20-cubit width of the inner sanctuary. The word <em>maʿăśeh ṣabbûʿ</em> (sculptured work — H6213) may indicate carved/sculpted wood rather than cast metal, overlaid with gold. These freestanding cherubim were in addition to the two cherubim on the ark's lid (Exod 25:18-20).</p>",
        "11": "<p><strong>kenap hakkĕrûḇ hāʾeḥad ḥamēš ʾammôt</strong> — 'The wing of one cherub was 5 cubits.' The geometry: each cherub had two wings of 5 cubits each (total wingspan = 10 cubits per cherub). With two cherubim positioned side-by-side, one outer wing of each cherub touched the walls (v12) while the two inner wings touched each other in the center (v13). This created a continuous canopy of overshadowing wings across the entire 20-cubit width of the inner sanctuary. The <em>kĕrûḇîm</em> faced the nave (<em>penê habbayit</em>) — that is, they faced outward toward the entering worshiper, with wings extended over the ark between them.</p>",
        "12": "<p><strong>vekenap hakkĕrûḇ hāʾaḥer ḥamēš ʾammôt maggaʿat beqîr habbayit</strong> — 'The other wing of that cherub, 5 cubits, touched the wall of the house.' The architectural positioning: each cherub's outer wing reached the wall, spanning the full 20-cubit width. The Chronicler's precise measurements establish this as a carefully engineered architectural space, not an improvised arrangement. The cherubim's function was to overshadow (<em>sākaḵ</em> — H5526, to cover, protect) the ark of the covenant — as the Tabernacle cherubim overshadowed the mercy seat where YHWH met Israel (Exod 25:22). The inner sanctuary is thus an amplification of the Tabernacle's core sacred space.</p>",
        "13": "<p><strong>kenepê hakkĕrûḇîm hāʾēlleh pōrĕśîm ʿeśrîm ʾammāh</strong> — 'The wings of these cherubim spread 20 cubits.' The summary geometry: combined wingspan of both cherubim = 20 cubits, exactly the width of the most holy place. The cherubim stood (<em>omdîm ʿal-ragleyhem</em>) on their feet — they were not prostrate but upright, like living guardians. <em>Ûfenêhem leḇêt</em> ('their faces toward the nave') means they faced the entrance to the inner sanctuary, watching over what entered. This orientation — guardians facing outward — parallels the cherubim of Eden who guarded the way to the tree of life (Gen 3:24), suggesting the inner sanctuary as an Eden-restoration.</p>",
        "14": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas ʾet-hapārokhet tĕkhēlet vaʾargāmān vekarmîl ûḇûts</strong> — 'He made the veil of violet, purple, crimson, and fine linen.' The <em>pārōkhet</em> (veil/curtain — H6532) separated the holy place from the most holy place — the barrier between the two areas of graded holiness. The four colors — <em>tĕkhēlet</em> (blue-violet, from the murex snail), <em>argāmān</em> (purple, a more expensive dye), <em>karmîl</em> (crimson, scarlet), and <em>ḇûts</em> (fine white linen) — reproduce exactly the Tabernacle veil's colors (Exod 26:31). The <em>kĕrûḇîm</em> woven into it continue the heavenly guardian motif. The veil literally stood between human and divine space.</p>",
        "15": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas lifnê habbayit ʿamûdîm šĕnayim</strong> — 'He made two pillars in front of the house.' The pillars <em>Yākhîn</em> (H3199 — 'He establishes/will establish') and <em>Bōʿaz</em> (H1162 — 'in him is strength') stood at the entrance of the Temple portico, 35 cubits tall with elaborate capital decorations. The names appear to be dedicatory inscriptions or liturgical formulas rather than structural labels — perhaps from a declaration made at the Temple's inauguration: 'He will establish [this house] / In him is strength.' The pillars had Phoenician antecedents (similar free-standing pillars appear at Phoenician temples) but their inscribed names give them distinctive Yahwistic meaning.</p>",
        "16": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas śarṣĕrôt biddəḇîr vayyittēn ʿal-rōʾš hāʿammûdîm</strong> — 'He made chains in the inner sanctuary and put them on the capitals of the pillars.' The <em>śarṣĕrôt</em> (chain garlands — H8333) were decorative chain-link festoons hung at the pillar capitals. The <em>rimmônîm</em> (pomegranates — H7416) numbered 100 per chain, hung on each capital. Pomegranates were symbols of fertility and abundance in the ancient Near East (appearing on priestly robes, Exod 28:33-34) and here adorn the boundary markers of YHWH's house. The capitals' decorative complexity — lily-work, chains, pomegranates — made them visual statements about the temple's sacred beauty.</p>",
        "17": "<p><strong>vayyāqem ʾet-hāʿammûdîm ʿal-penê hahêkhāl</strong> — 'He erected the pillars in front of the nave.' The positioning — <em>ʿal-penê hahêkhāl</em> (in front of the nave/hall) — places Jachin and Boaz at the Temple's main entrance, flanking the doorway. Every Israelite entering would pass between or beside these pillars, whose names proclaimed YHWH's faithfulness. The right-hand pillar <em>Yākhîn</em> and left-hand <em>Bōʿaz</em> created an architecturally defined threshold of divine-human encounter. Later biblical imagery of the righteous standing like pillars in God's house (Ps 92:12-14; Rev 3:12) likely draws on these physical pillars as metaphoric precedent.</p>",
    },
    "4": {
        "1": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas mizbaḥ neḥōšet ʿeśrîm ʾammāh ʾorkô</strong> — 'He made a bronze altar 20 cubits long.' The <em>mizbaḥ neḥōšet</em> (bronze altar — H4196, H5178) was the primary sacrificial surface — 20 cubits long, 20 wide, and 10 high (vs. Bezalel's Tabernacle altar of 5×5×3 cubits in Exod 27:1). The fourfold enlargement reflects the Temple's greater scale: a larger altar was needed for the vastly larger animal offerings anticipated at the new national sanctuary. The bronze altar represents the sacrificial theology at the temple's heart: access to YHWH requires atonement through blood sacrifice.</p>",
        "3": "<p><strong>ûdĕmût šĕnê śĕrāpîm taḥat hayyām missāḇîḇ</strong> — 'Under the sea, all around, were two rows of decorations.' The <em>śĕrāpîm</em> (oxen-figures — though the text is difficult; some read <em>pĕqāʿîm</em>, gourd shapes) circled the base of the Sea in two rows per cubit, cast together with the vessel. The molten sea (<em>yam muṣāq</em> — H3220, H3332) was a massive circular bronze basin: 10 cubits in diameter, 5 cubits deep, with a circumference of 30 cubits. The 3:1 circumference-to-diameter ratio suggests the Chronicler (or his source) was using an approximation of π. The Sea's capacity (3,000 baths) made it the largest single bronze object cast in the ancient Near East.</p>",
        "4": "<p><strong>ʿomed ʿal-šenê ʿāśār bāqār šelōšāh pōnîm tsāfônāh</strong> — 'It stood on 12 oxen, three facing north.' The <em>šenê ʿāśār bāqār</em> (twelve oxen) supporting the Sea were arranged in four groups of three, facing the four cardinal directions (north, west, south, east). The compass arrangement (<em>tsāfôn, yam, negev, mizrāḥ</em>) is cosmologically significant — the Sea resting on the four-directional oxen symbolizes the ordered cosmos under divine sovereignty. In Canaanite iconography the bull was a symbol of divine strength; here twelve bulls (the number of Israel's tribes) support the sacred water, mapping Israel's tribal identity onto a cosmic symbol.</p>",
        "5": "<p><strong>ûḇê yādô ṭepah sōwgô</strong> — 'Its thickness was a handbreadth.' The precise metalwork specifications: wall thickness = 1 <em>tepah</em> (handbreadth ≈ 7.5 cm), rim shaped like a lily flower (<em>śûśan</em>), capacity = 3,000 <em>bat</em> (baths, approximately 22,000 liters). The lily-rim (<em>ûpîhû keʿăśeh pî-kôs perāḥ šûšan</em> — 'its mouth was like the work of a cup's mouth, a lily flower') echoes the lily-work on the pillar capitals (ch3:17). The <em>šûšan</em>-lily motif was common in Phoenician art. The combination of structural precision and decorative beauty reflects the Chronicler's theology: the temple's craft is as important as its liturgy.</p>",
        "6": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas kiyyôrôt ʿăśārāh</strong> — 'He made 10 basins.' The <em>kiyyôrôt</em> (lavers/basins — H3595) were ten smaller bronze basins for washing sacrificial offerings (<em>laraḥōts bāhem maʿăśēh hāʿōlāh yādîḥû bām</em> — 'to wash with them the work of the burnt offering they rinse in them'). Five stood on each side of the nave (v6). The Sea (<em>yam</em>) served a different function: priestly ritual washing (1 Kgs 7:26 specifies it was 'for the priests to wash'). The ten lavers match the ten lampstands and ten tables (vv7-8), creating a symmetrical liturgical space. The parallel fivefold arrangement on each side maps temple geography onto Israel's bilateral covenant structure.</p>",
        "7": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas ʾet-mĕnôrôt hazzāhāḇ ʿeśer kammišpāṭ</strong> — 'He made 10 golden lampstands as prescribed.' The <em>mĕnôrôt</em> (lampstands — H4501, singular <em>mĕnôrāh</em>) were ten in number (vs. the Tabernacle's single seven-branched lampstand — Exod 25:31), placed in the holy place (five on each side). The phrase <em>kammišpāṭ</em> (according to the rule/ordinance) signals that the lampstands' design followed the Mosaic specification — they were not new inventions but scaled expressions of the original pattern. Light (<em>ʾôr</em>) in the windowless holy place was entirely lamp-dependent, making the lampstands essential for the daily liturgy of the priestly service.</p>",
        "8": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas šulḥānôt ʿăśārāh vayyayyaḥ bāhêkāl</strong> — 'He made ten tables and placed them in the nave.' The <em>šulḥānôt</em> (tables — H7979) numbered ten vs. the Tabernacle's single Table of the Presence (Exod 25:23-30). Their function was to hold the <em>leḥem hapānîm</em> (bread of the Presence/showbread — twelve loaves set before YHWH each week). Ten tables allowed far more bread to be presented simultaneously, proportionate to the temple's greater scale. The <em>mizrāqôt</em> (bowls for sprinkling — H4219) were also gold — the Chronicler specifies <em>zahāḇ</em> (gold) throughout, emphasizing that nothing in the temple's service equipment was base metal.</p>",
        "9": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas ḥătsar hakkōhănîm</strong> — 'He made the court of the priests.' The <em>ḥătsar hakkōhănîm</em> (priests' court) was an inner court, distinct from the larger outer court. The <em>ezrāh haggĕdôlāh</em> (great court) surrounded it. The doors (<em>dĕlātôt</em>) to these courts were bronze-plated. The graduated courts — outer (for all Israel), inner (for priests), inner sanctuary (for the high priest on Yom Kippur) — established the spatial theology of holiness gradation: the closer to the divine presence, the more restricted the access. This spatial hierarchy was not exclusion but protection — the holy God's presence required commensurate purity.</p>",
        "10": "<p><strong>veʾet-hayyām nātan mikkātēp hayyĕmānît qēdmāh</strong> — 'He placed the Sea on the right side, to the southeast.' The Sea's placement (<em>mikkātēp hayyĕmānît qēdmāh</em> — 'on the right shoulder, toward the east') means the southeast corner of the inner court, at the priests' entrance. Every priest entering the inner court for service would pass by the Sea used for ritual washing. The precise compass location — southeast — may have cosmological significance, as east was the direction of sunrise and the Temple's main entrance faced east, aligning the building with the rising sun and the direction of YHWH's coming glory (Ezek 43:2).</p>",
        "11": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas ḥûrām ʾet-hassîrôt veʾet-hayyāʿîm veʾet-hammizrāqôt</strong> — 'Huram made the pots, shovels, and bowls.' The bronze vessels of daily priestly service: <em>sîrôt</em> (pots — H5518, for boiling sacrificial meat), <em>yaʿîm</em> (shovels — H3257, for removing ashes), <em>mizrāqôt</em> (bowls — H4219, for receiving and tossing blood). These practical implements received the same craftsmanship attention as the decorative items — function and beauty were not separated in the temple's liturgical equipment. The phrase <em>vayyekhal ḥûrām laʿăśôt</em> ('Huram finished making') marks the completion of the craftsman's commission, a formal conclusion to his temple contribution.</p>",
        "12": "<p><strong>ʾet-šeney hāʿammûdîm vehaggullōt vehaggullōt vehaggullôt</strong> — 'the two pillars, the capitals on top of the pillars.' The inventory of Huram's work continues, recounting the completed pieces: the two freestanding pillars (Jachin and Boaz), their bowl-shaped capitals (<em>gullôt</em> — H1543), the double net-work garlands decorating each capital, the 400 pomegranates (<em>200 per capital</em>) in two rows. The recapitulation of ch3's architectural details confirms that all the commissioned work was successfully completed — the Chronicler uses the inventory as an implicit verification of Huram's faithful craftsmanship to the king's specifications.</p>",
        "13": "<p><strong>ʾarbaʿ meʾôt rimmônîm lišetê haśśbekākôt</strong> — '400 pomegranates for the two sets of network.' The double rows of 100 pomegranates on each capital (2 × 2 × 100 = 400) created a ring of fruit-shapes around each pillar head. The <em>rimmôn</em> (pomegranate — H7416) was a fertility and abundance symbol throughout the ancient Near East — appearing on Egyptian columns, Phoenician ivories, and Israelite priestly vestments. In the temple context, the pomegranate's many seeds suggested the abundance of blessing flowing from YHWH's presence. The painstaking detail of 400 individually cast pomegranates reflects the investment of extraordinary craftsmanship in what were ultimately decorative elements.</p>",
        "14": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas ʾet-hakkĕnôt vayyaʿas ʾet-hakiyôrôt ʿal-hakkĕnôt</strong> — 'He made the stands, and made the basins on the stands.' The <em>mĕkhônôt</em> (wheeled stands — H4350) were elaborate bronze cart-like structures described in detail in 1 Kgs 7:27-39. Each stand was 4 cubits long, 4 wide, and 3 high, with decorative panels showing lions, oxen, cherubim, and palm trees. The wheels allowed them to be moved — they were portable washing stations for the priestly service. The ten basins (one per stand) sat on top. The Chronicler's abbreviated account points the reader to Kings for the technical details while summarizing: all were made, all were functional.</p>",
        "15": "<p><strong>vehayyām ʾeḥād ûbāqār šenêm ʿāśār taḥtāyw</strong> — 'The one Sea and the twelve oxen under it.' The summary of major bronze pieces concludes with the Sea — the largest single item. The twelve oxen (<em>šenêm ʿāśār bāqār</em>) supporting it are recalled, completing the inventory of major liturgical items. The entire bronze complex represented an extraordinary achievement of ancient metallurgy: the casting of the Sea alone (3,000 baths capacity, walls one handbreadth thick) would have required a massive industrial infrastructure of furnaces, clay molds, and skilled bronze workers. Huram-abi's accomplishment was unprecedented in Israel's history.</p>",
        "16": "<p><strong>veʾet-hassîrôt veʾet-hayyāʿîm veʾet-hammizlāgôt</strong> — 'The pots, shovels, and forks.' The subsidiary bronze utensils are enumerated: <em>sîrôt</em> (cooking pots), <em>yaʿîm</em> (ash-shovels), <em>mizlāgôt</em> (flesh-hooks/forks — H4207, for handling meat in the sacrificial process). The phrase <em>kol-kēlêhem ʿāśāh ḥûrām ʾāḇîhū lamelekh shelomoh bêt YHWH</em> ('all these vessels Huram-abi made for King Solomon for the house of YHWH') is the craftsman's completion formula. Every item, from the massive Sea to the small flesh-hooks, was purpose-made for YHWH's house — nothing was repurposed from secular use.</p>",
        "17": "<p><strong>bekkikkār hayardēn yĕtsāqām hammelekh bĕʾadāmāh</strong> — 'In the plain of the Jordan the king cast them.' The <em>kikkār hayardēn</em> (Jordan plain/circuit) — specifically <em>bêt ʾaḇārāh</em> (Succoth) and <em>tsĕrēdāh</em> (Zarethan) of 1 Kgs 7:46 — provided the clay-rich riverbanks ideal for large-scale casting. Bronze casting required dense, moisture-retaining clay for molds. The Jordan Valley's alluvial clay was evidently of higher quality than Judean clay, requiring the major casting work to be done near Succoth. The logistical challenge of transporting finished bronzework from the Jordan Valley to Jerusalem (~60 km, gaining ~1000m elevation) underscores the scale of Solomon's enterprise.</p>",
        "18": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas shelomoh ʾet-kol-hakkēlîm hāʾēlleh lārōḇ meʾōd</strong> — 'Solomon made all these objects in such great quantity.' <em>Lārōḇ meʾōd</em> (in very great quantity/abundance) summarizes the scale of the bronze program. The statement that <em>wĕlōʾ neḥqar mišqal hanneḥōšet</em> (the weight of the bronze was not determined) may reflect the unprecedented quantity — the palace archives did not even track the total. This echoes the earlier statement that silver and gold became as common as stones (1:15). The Chronicler uses deliberate hyperbole to portray Solomon's temple-building as a work of cosmic abundance, befitting a house for the God of Israel.</p>",
        "19": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas shelomoh ʾet kol-hakkēlîm ʾăšer bêt hāʾĕlōhîm</strong> — 'Solomon made all the objects that were in the house of God.' The transition from bronze to gold: the exterior bronze items (altar, Sea, lavers) gave way to the interior gold items — the altar of incense (<em>mizbaḥ hazzāhāḇ</em>), the tables for the bread of the Presence (<em>šulḥānôt lehem hapānîm</em>), the lampstands. The <em>zāhāḇ ṭāhôr</em> (pure gold) specification for interior items reflects the holiness gradation: the closer to the divine presence, the purer the metal. Bronze was adequate for the sacrificial courts; only gold was appropriate for the space where YHWH's name dwelt.</p>",
        "20": "<p><strong>veʾet-hakkĕrûḇîm veʾet-hattimôrôt</strong> — 'and the cherubim and the palm trees.' The flowering (<em>perāḥ</em>) lampstands and their features recall the Tabernacle menorah (Exod 25:31-40) — almond blossoms, calyxes, and branches. The temple's lampstands (<em>kammišpāṭ liḇnê-qōdĕš haqqĕdāšîm</em> — 'as prescribed for the inner sanctuary') maintained the exact Mosaic pattern while multiplying it tenfold. Light in the inner sanctuary was permanent and non-natural — the lamps burned continuously (Exod 27:20), maintained by priests. They symbolized YHWH's unceasing presence in Israel's midst, a light that never went out even through Israel's darkest periods.</p>",
        "21": "<p><strong>vehaperāḥîm vehannerôt vehammelqāḥayim zahāḇ hûʾ</strong> — 'The flowers, the lamps, and the tongs — gold.' The inventory of pure gold items includes <em>perāḥîm</em> (blossoms/flowers, decorative elements), <em>nerôt</em> (lamps — H5216, oil cups), and <em>melqāḥayim</em> (snuffers/tongs — H4457, for trimming lamp wicks). The word <em>zahāḇ hûʾ</em> ('it was gold') functions as an emphatic refrain — every single item, no matter how small or functional, was made of gold. Even the snuffers used to trim lamp wicks were gold. The total commitment to gold for interior furnishings was Israel's most lavish material statement about the incomparable worth of YHWH's presence.</p>",
        "22": "<p><strong>vehamzammĕrôt vehamizrāqôt vehakayyôt vehamachtôt zahāḇ ṭāhôr</strong> — 'The knives, sprinkling bowls, cups, and fire-holders — pure gold.' The final gold inventory: <em>mezammĕrôt</em> (pruning knives/snuffers), <em>mizrāqôt</em> (sprinkling bowls), <em>kappôt</em> (spoons/cups — H3709, used for incense), <em>maḥtôt</em> (fire-holders/censers — H4289). The phrase <em>ûpetaḥ habbayit dĕlātāyw haPnîmiyyôt lĕqōdĕš haqqĕdāšîm</em> (the inner door of the house, its inner doors to the most holy place) closes the furnishings inventory with the two inner gold doors — the physical boundary between holy and most-holy — made entirely of gold. The temple's interior was a golden world, earthly approximation of the heavenly sanctuary.</p>",
    },
    "5": {
        "1": "<p><strong>vattiššlam kol-hamĕlāʾkhāh ʾăšer-ʿāśāh shelomoh</strong> — 'All the work that Solomon did for the house of YHWH was completed.' The completion formula (<em>vattiššlam</em> — H7999, to be complete, finished, whole; the root of <em>šālôm</em>) marks the end of the building phase. Everything (<em>kol hakkēlîm</em>) that David had dedicated — the silver, gold, and temple vessels — Solomon brought in and placed in the temple treasuries (<em>ôtserôt bêt hāʾĕlōhîm</em>). This verse fulfills the Davidic vision (1 Chr 22, 28-29): David prepared the materials, and Solomon completed the work. The word <em>šālôm</em> is embedded in Solomon's name (<em>Šelomoh</em>) — his reign was the reign of completion and wholeness.</p>",
        "2": "<p><strong>ʾāz yaqhēl shelomoh ʾet-ziqnê yisrāʾel</strong> — 'Then Solomon assembled the elders of Israel.' The ark's installation required a second great national assembly, this time at the feast of the seventh month (<em>beḥag hūʾ haḥōdeš hashŏḇîʿî</em> — Tabernacles, the feast of ingathering). The <em>ziqnê yisrāʾel</em> (elders), <em>kol-rāʾšê hammattôt</em> (heads of tribes), and <em>nĕśîʾê haʾăḇôt liḇnê yisrāʾel</em> (leaders of the ancestral houses) — all leadership strata gathered. This comprehensive assembly mirrors the Sinai covenant gathering (Exod 24:1) and the Deuteronomic assembly (Deut 29:10), grounding the temple dedication in Israel's covenant history.</p>",
        "3": "<p><strong>vayyiqqāhălû ʾel-hammelekh kol-ʾîš yisrāʾel beḥag hūʾ haḥōdeš hashŏḇîʿî</strong> — 'All the men of Israel assembled to the king at the feast, in the seventh month.' The Feast of Tabernacles (<em>Sukkôt</em>) was the annual completion of the agricultural year, the feast of the gathered harvest, and the occasion for national covenant renewal (Deut 31:10-13). Choosing this feast for the ark's installation was theologically deliberate: just as YHWH had dwelt with Israel in the wilderness in a tent (<em>sukkāh</em>), now the ark came to its permanent dwelling — the feast of tents became the occasion for the end of tent-dwelling. Wilderness wandering ended; permanent habitation in the land was being consecrated.</p>",
        "4": "<p><strong>vayyāḇôʾû kol-ziqnê yisrāʾel vayyiśśĕʾû halĕwîyyim ʾet-hāʾārôn</strong> — 'All the elders of Israel came, and the Levites took up the ark.' The Chronicler specifies <em>halĕwîyyim</em> (Levites) as the ark-bearers, distinguishing this from the tragic incident of 1 Chr 13 (when non-Levites touched the ark and Uzzah died). David had corrected this (1 Chr 15:2): 'None ought to carry the ark of God but the Levites.' Solomon's installation follows the Mosaic-Davidic protocol precisely. The Levites carrying the ark on their shoulders by the poles (Num 4:15; Deut 10:8) was the prescribed method — physical separation between the holy object and human hands.</p>",
        "5": "<p><strong>vayyaʿălû ʾet-hāʾārôn vaʾet-ʾōhel môʿēd veʾet-kol-kəlê haqqōdĕš</strong> — 'They brought up the ark, the Tent of Meeting, and all the holy vessels.' The inclusion of <em>ʾōhel môʿēd</em> (the Tent of Meeting) is significant — the Mosaic Tabernacle itself was brought to Jerusalem and incorporated into the temple proceedings. All its sacred vessels came too (<em>veʾet-kol-kĕlê haqqōdĕš</em>). The priests (<em>hakkōhănîm</em>) and the Levites carried everything. This merging of Tabernacle and Temple traditions was the Chronicler's way of showing continuity: the new temple did not replace the Mosaic tradition but fulfilled and incorporated it. The old dwelling-place ended its pilgrimage by arriving at its permanent home.</p>",
        "6": "<p><strong>vehammelekh shelomoh wekhol-ʿădat yisrāʾel hannoʿādîm ʿālāyw</strong> — 'King Solomon and all the congregation of Israel assembled before the ark.' The sacrificial scale is extraordinary: <em>tsōn ûḇāqār ʾăšer lōʾ-yissāpĕrû vĕlōʾ yimmānû merōḇ</em> ('sheep and oxen which could not be counted or numbered because of the multitude'). The language deliberately echoes the innumerable Israelites (2 Chr 1:9) — just as the people were beyond counting, so were the animals offered at this dedication. Every Israelite tribe was represented; the entire nation participated in the liturgical act of consecrating YHWH's dwelling. The sacrifices constituted Israel's communal declaration that this temple was YHWH's rightful place.</p>",
        "7": "<p><strong>vayyāḇîʾû hakkōhănîm ʾet-ʾărôn berît-YHWH</strong> — 'The priests brought in the ark of the covenant of YHWH.' The ark's full title — <em>ʾărôn berît-YHWH</em> (ark of the covenant of YHWH) — appears here for the first time in Chronicles' temple narrative, reminding that the ark was Israel's covenant document-holder, containing the two stone tablets of the Ten Commandments. The destination: <em>el-dĕḇîr habbayit ʾel-qōdĕš haqqĕdāšîm</em> (to the inner sanctuary of the house, to the most holy place). The ark traveled from its wilderness home to its final earthly resting place — underneath the great cherubim whose wings would overshadow it.</p>",
        "8": "<p><strong>vayyihyû hakkĕrûḇîm pōrĕśîm knāpayim</strong> — 'The cherubim spread out their wings.' The positioning: the two great cherubim (<em>kĕrûḇîm</em>) of the inner sanctuary spread their wings over (<em>ʿal māqôm hāʾārôn</em>) the place of the ark, sheltering (<em>sakkĕkhû</em> — H5526, to cover, screen, protect) the ark and its poles from above. The ark's carrying poles were long enough to be visible from the holy place but not from outside the inner sanctuary — a detail (v9) indicating the proportions of the space. The imagery is of divine protection: the cherubim's wings formed a canopy of safety over Israel's covenant charter, parallel to the wings of God Himself who protects Israel under His wings (Ps 91:4; Ruth 2:12).</p>",
        "9": "<p><strong>vayyaʾarîkhû habbaddîm vayyērāʾû rāʾšê habbaddîm</strong> — 'The poles extended; the ends of the poles were visible.' The carrying poles (<em>baddîm</em> — H905, extended staves through rings on the ark's sides) were long enough to project slightly beyond the veil into the holy place, without being fully visible to those outside the inner sanctuary. This detail (absent in the MT of 1 Kgs 8:8 but present in Kgs' Greek) is architecturally precise: the poles were approximately 10+ cubits long, passing through the inner veil. Their visibility from the holy place but not from outside served as a visual reminder that the ark was present even when unseen — YHWH was there, behind the veil.</p>",
        "10": "<p><strong>ʾên bāʾārôn raq šenê halluḥôt</strong> — 'There was nothing in the ark except the two tablets.' The emphasis on the ark's sole contents — <em>šenê halluḥôt</em> (the two tablets, H3871), the Sinai covenant documents (<em>ʾăšer kārat YHWH ʿim-bĕnê yisrāʾel bĕṣēʾtām mimmitsrāyim</em> — 'which YHWH cut with the sons of Israel when they came out of Egypt') — is theologically pointed. The ark contained only the covenant law. The golden jar of manna and Aaron's rod (Heb 9:4) are not mentioned here; the Chronicler focuses on the ark as covenant-keeper, the repository of YHWH's binding words to Israel. The physical core of the temple is YHWH's own word: law is at the center of worship.</p>",
        "11": "<p><strong>vayhî beṣēt hakkōhănîm min-haqqōdĕš</strong> — 'When the priests came out of the holy place.' All priests present had consecrated themselves regardless of their division assignments (<em>kol-hakkōhănîm haʾăšer-nimtsĕʾû hitqaddĕšû</em>) — this was not a rotation service but a national event requiring every available priest. The Levites were all positioned: <em>haʾăsāp, hêmān, ûyedûtûn, ûḇěnêhem ûʾăḥêhem</em> (Asaph, Heman, Jeduthun, their sons and brothers) stood east of the altar, dressed in fine linen, with cymbals, harps, and lyres, alongside 120 priests with trumpets (<em>ḥotsotserôt</em>). The full complement of Israel's musical ministry gathered for this supreme moment.</p>",
        "12": "<p><strong>vayyihyû hamĕšorĕrîm ûlĕwîyyim kullām</strong> — 'All the Levite singers were present.' The Chronicler's description of the musical assembly is unmatched in its detail: Asaph, Heman, and Jeduthun's families — the three guilds established by David (1 Chr 25) — with their sons and brothers. One hundred twenty priests with trumpets completed the ensemble. The phrase <em>kemitswa ʾaḥad lehallēl ûlehôdôt lAYHWH</em> (as one unit, to praise and give thanks to YHWH) — the whole ensemble played and sang in unison. When <em>berîm kōl wayĕrîm baqôl</em> (they lifted their voice to praise YHWH), the entire temple complex was filled with communal worship.</p>",
        "13": "<p><strong>vayhî keʾeḥād lemĕḥatserĕrîm ûlĕmĕšorĕrîm</strong> — 'When the trumpeters and singers were as one.' The climactic moment: the musicians' unity (<em>keʾeḥād</em> — literally 'as one') produced a single sound (<em>qôl eḥad</em>). The liturgical refrain they sang: <em>hôdû laYHWH kî ṭôḇ kî leʿôlām ḥasdô</em> — 'Give thanks to YHWH, for he is good, for his steadfast love endures forever.' This was Israel's great doxology (Ps 136; 1 Chr 16:34,41), the covenant formula that expressed YHWH's unchanging character. As this word of praise filled the temple, <em>habbayit</em> was filled with a cloud (<em>ʿānān</em>) — the divine response was immediate: where Israel praised YHWH's covenant faithfulness, He manifested His glory.</p>",
        "14": "<p><strong>wĕlōʾ-yākhĕlû hakkōhănîm laʿămōd lĕšārēt</strong> — 'The priests could not stand to minister.' The divine <em>kāḇôd</em> (glory — H3519) filled the temple in the form of a thick cloud (<em>ʿānān</em> — H6051). The cloud of glory was YHWH's characteristic theophany: it led Israel through the wilderness (Exod 13:21), settled on Sinai (Exod 24:15-18), and filled the Tabernacle at its dedication so that Moses could not enter (Exod 40:34-35). Now the same glory filled the Temple — the continuity between Mosaic and Solomonic worship was validated by God Himself. The priests being physically unable to stand or serve (<em>mippenê hāʿānān kî māle ḵĕḇôd-YHWH ʾet-bêt hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) demonstrated that this was not a human institution but a divine habitation.</p>",
    }
}

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: Merge new commentary entries without overwriting existing ones — safe to re-run
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

out_path = pathlib.Path("data/commentary/mkt-original/2chronicles.json")
existing = json.loads(out_path.read_text()) if out_path.exists() else {}
before = sum(len(existing.get(c, {})) for c in DATA)
merge_comm(existing, DATA)
after = sum(len(existing.get(c, {})) for c in DATA)
out_path.write_text(json.dumps(existing, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2))
print(f"  wrote {out_path}")
print(f"2chronicles mkt-original: added up to {after - before} verses across ch1-5")
